segments.text: Interview with Mr. D.A.
Anderson, side four.
When we were talking about the place of changing the voting to at-large, and maybe we've mentioned this before, but you said that things were not being, things on the council weren't able to be done.
There was always the opposition from...
And then, knowing that they went in, you know what I mean, with a very limited number of votes, this wasn't right.
And the people were worked up, as I indicated earlier.
They came to the council, and I gave them an opportunity to see them turn down things that I wanted passed, that the people wanted passed.
And they just refused right before the eyes of the public.
And that made them mad enough that they wanted to send around a petition to get them off the council.
So I told them we'll just wait.
It wasn't too long before I could get the time period.
before they went off to council.
And then they came wanting to know who I wanted to put on the council.
And so we got everything squared up for the next election.
And when the next election came, why, we had these other council members.
And then we approached the subject of more equity in voting.
And so then the voting lines were changed.
Well, they've been changed several times since.
When the ruling came, for example, and the students could vote, that imposed another problem.
So, that was something else.
And they were changed then.
So, in essence, that's it.
Have you already mentioned when we said that they kept things from being done, what kind of things were they stopping?
Well, I couldn't get anything passed.
Oh, okay.
I mean, it was a matter of anything that I wanted, you know.
We weren't making any progress at all in the city.
We just wanted to go, but we couldn't go.
I mean, it's time.

and we were no longer a little community and we had to think big and move big and move out and as you know when you're reading why from then on why you didn't make very strident moves towards doing a lot of things we mentioned the library
Well, you can go into any of the areas in the area that we were trying to turn it with.
In the old days, you know, my city manager got picked up a car every year.
And then the next year, or the year that he picked up his new car, well, the police chief got the other car that he had.
I mean, that's the way everything was passed on.
from one to the other.
And they got through, or went through the sewer to, well, sewer disposal plant, or some other plant.
And incidentally, there is a report someplace in there, too, where, of course, I had a good friend in Garrison, he was head of the Department of Public Safety in Washington.
And this is the only city in the state of Texas where he did this, and he did this as a favor to me.
Now, he originally from Luffman, and I used to live in Luffman, and I knew him very well.
And I wanted to know if he would come in and evaluate our police department, let me know what we needed, what was good, what was desirable, and so on.
So he sent in two or three men, sometimes every three men, to evaluate and make a report to me and the city council on our police department.
And they went with the department.
They covered everything from the type of uniforms to their guns to their weakness in training, every aspect of law enforcement.

and this was very very good because it pointed out not only to me but to other council members where all the weaknesses were in our police department in terms of its future expansion i mean we have something to go about which we haven't had and this is the only city in the state of mexico
Did you run into it?
No, I didn't.
But it did ring to mind when I did run into it, and that was a fire department.
Was it also during this period that you and the council decided to try to establish a college station fire department?
Oh, yeah.
Totally did.
Right.
And remove yourself from A&M?
Yeah.
Yeah.
But this enabled us to move out because, you know, they wore different uniforms.
Should we buy things?
Should we buy the yachts?
Should we buy the uniforms?
You know, what would strengthen the department and all this stuff.
We've got an excellent report.
I have pride in myself.
You know, this is one other area that I wanted to improve and I'm glad that DPS did it.
I'm sorry again that I didn't make a copy of that.
There are certain things that I don't understand.
The same thing with that Negro report that they went from house to house.
That was a pretty expensive report.
They told me, they said, now we've made a lot of surveys for the city, but we're not saying it was accurate.
This is accurate.
And of course there are places on which I helped them on too.
But that report is something we need to prioritize more.
And that other report will be the only one of its kind.
The DPS turned it down.
No other city got that service.
That's one of them.
Did a lot of College Station's growth and your concern about the growth of the city spring from the fact that A&M was also growing at that time?
Yeah, sure.
You know, you could see, you could sense the growth coming more and more.
The day would come, not too far distant, that you would need the blockchain right.
And there's still
You know what I mean.
There are still those that grind.
I don't know whether you're aware of what's going on at the Humana Hospital.
No, I'm not.
Humana wants to get out of there and come out.
They didn't get any support from certain crime people when they were trying to expand.
I don't know whether it was political or not, but...
They're just, they don't want the crawler station to get you in any circumstance.
And there's a committee formed that way.
Leave no stone unturned to be sure that the crawler station doesn't give you any lessons.
It's resentment.
That's some of the following.
They dread, they just would rather, I mean, it's funny because...
People's good are set aside for, I guess, for a type of vanity.
Yeah.
I'm not sure the word.
Yeah, yeah.
Well, it's a, you know, you have to understand a lot of that background sometimes and appreciate some, you know, certain things.
And having gone through a lot of it myself, you know, going over there.
I'd like to talk about the lawsuit that was brought against the city during your term.
And I was wondering how the lawsuit evolved and what Boyan's purpose in bringing a suit against the city.
Well, he said
that we were holding two offices in trust.
We held a position with the university and either councilman or mayor with the city of Colorado State.
Now, what prompted that?
Now, that had previously come up.
You may have seen the attorney general opinion

of 1938 you read that and they said it was all right and they have said it was all right right along up until that period uh this was an effort by him to uh i know he was after me but he got the whole council now
What brought this on was the matter of zoning that he didn't like over in this particular area.
That was his domain.
He was being elected on 21 votes.
You know, he was throwing his weight around.
He had money.
It was very interesting during the end of the year to see how, well I better not say that.
Well, no, that's all right.
He disliked the treatment he was receiving because he couldn't have it his own way.
He had some trouble with the university earlier.
He had trouble with the student body and whatnot.
But be that as it may, he resented very much
So, he brought this suit.
He was no longer counsel.
He went around and picked up some things and got Joe married.
And how Joe got on?
He dropped out?
Yeah, it took him quite a bit of money to drop out.
Right, about $200,000.
Oh, it took him more than that.
We were laughing about it the other day.
He picked up my, every time I went, he picked up my check.
He still apologizes to me for that.
But at any rate, they brought this suit and brought us into court here.
And Judge Davis has worked more than I did.
Well, Bill is a friend of the university, a friend of the city council, a friend of the county.
Bill was, you know, just, do you know Bill Bishop?
I don't know him.
Oh.
Does he still lie?
Oh, he was very, you know, very well-liked, and we liked him for sitting on the judge continually, and he didn't think we'd have a lady to stand on and voted in our favor.
And Boyette made the statement that he's going to carry this work to the U.S. And he has the money.
And look at the money he's still making at that time.
He has no choice.
Does he own the land?
All of those stores are leased by him.
But be that as it may, he was determined that he was going to bring home the U.S. Supreme Court instead.
So he took us over to the district court in Boston.
And the judge over there .
Oh, really?
Over in Boston.
Over in Joe?
Yeah, in Joe.
Was it Brendan for you?
I didn't realize that.
That's another story.
But he then ruled this area.
We had to go over there twice.
Oh, he never did rule.
Boyad carried it down to the District U.S. Court in Houston.
And the federal judge ruled.
It was a surprise to us when it came.
that the ruling of the Attorney General wasn't there and that we were out.
I mean, we had to be out.
And there was nothing else he could do beyond that.
I mean, he had gone.
He had the money to do it.
We were criticized for letting the city pay
The attorney, we hired an attorney in Houston, and the city paid for it.
I forgot what the amount was.
But O.E.
and his were the two sides of that.
That was the only protection we had.
Otherwise, but we...
They won.
Well, then it was following this that I took the action that I did independently and passed it down to them.
All right, buddy, if you think you got me, go ahead.
And then I did.
I did.
I'm not kidding you with that.
I worked a day and night, blood, sweat, and tears, too.
I was determined that I would protect the Constitution.
So, I mean, you took the lead in the state and moved.
Oh, yeah.
I was the only one that did it.
I had to.
Even though it affected others?
Oh, yeah.
It's like it affected school districts?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, there was a principle involved.
You know, I just...
I just couldn't have, you know, I couldn't lay down.
I just had to go.
So, we won.
Eddie wanted me to go back as mayor, and I said, no, I've got to go back now.
Oh, really?
I was wondering why he never returned.
Oh, I don't know.
It was a bad thing.
He wanted me to run for county judge.
I didn't want that.
I didn't care.
It was a problem for me.
I don't know.
Some of them wanted me to run for mayor at that time.
I wouldn't want it.
No, there's a lot going on.
Well, you know, I've had my share of that.
Why go in?
I haven't been to, you know, a lot of people.
For some of them, for some of the old-timers, they still expect me to run around with a tie and a coat.
You know, old people, for some reason.
Well, during the trial,
Boyant couldn't explain, I mean, his ulterior reason was that the city wasn't allowing him to do what he wanted him to do.
No, no, no.
He didn't bring that up.
Right, right.
What he was trying to say is that we were holding two offices in trust.
His ulterior motive was never brought up.
Well, I mean, how did he show that it affected the city...
in a harmful way?
Well, there was no business people who were representative of it.
We needed people who were on the city council to represent the business interests.
Actually, we didn't have too many people of business.
This was really a university community.
Right.
Primarily.
He was saying that the council was doing things specifically for Indians.
Well, he, in part of the court proceedings, he accused us of that.
For example, the lighting on the other side of the campus.
Oh, he brought up the underpass.
He always brought that up.
I never understood him because he was worth millions of dollars.
He never helped.
He never contributed to a student body.
You know what I mean.
He never contributed anything.
Kind of like he resented the university for some reason.
I don't know.
He had all the money he needed.
He had his summer home up in the lake.
I've been up on his plane for years.
We got along great.
Invited up there.
There were other people that signed the suit, and there was a question of whether or not the people really knew what they were signing.
Did they realize that they were going to bring a suit against the city?
Joe did, he said.
Do you know how, the way it represented it in San Diego?
Oh, no.
Well, I heard Joe say, you know, we need to petition.
We need to get more business people on the city council.
Now, the business people were the few motels that were here, Western and Joe at that time.
And let's see, was there another one?
Oh, yeah, there was one across the street.
Well, there were a few motels, service stations, there was a bank.
You know what I mean.
They were representing the business community.
And other than Boyette, the others didn't seem to be playing.
But, oh, now there were some, there was a grocery store in Southside, the dentist, and a few things like this.
But really, they weren't concerned as much as Boyev was.
He, I think this was mainly an excuse in terms of, you know, his feeling towards those who looked at him this way.
There were others on the council, of course, objecting to it.
Well, after I got in and got the other, you know, had my way there, why, uh, Marcy couldn't, couldn't do anything for me.
I didn't make sure that, uh,
We thought it was proper and just.
Well, was he upset that he had lost the election?
Oh yeah, he had it.
Yeah, he didn't even speak to me.
And he eventually died.
I felt sorry for him, too.
He was somewhat of a loner.
I think he was turned on by another organization.
He was turned on, and I think he was at that meeting.
I think he was not an extrovert.
I'm not sure.
He was very spontaneous.
That's part of it.
Some of the council members resigned, and you still stayed on.
Do you remember encouraging people to run?
When was this?
Well, during the suit.
The ruling came through that you could not hold office and receive your warrant.
Yeah, some of them.
So they were forced to resign.
Yeah, I went off for three months.
I don't know when the others went off.
Well, you were the last to leave before Jim Dozier.
Jim Dozier stayed on.
Yeah, he was the one that remained until I think the...
I think the Texas Supreme Court wouldn't hear it, and it would take several years before the Supreme Court could hear it.
I know it was all appeal.
But in the meantime, she didn't check with me.
No, no.
That's what the wife told me.
You can't eat unprincipled.
You can't eat unprincipled, right.
But...
Do you remember encouraging Mr. Vaughn or Mr. Luther to come?
Oh, yeah, I encouraged him.
I was really behind.
What we did, maybe this wasn't proper, but I thought it was.
I had sort of a committee to get together, made up of people from different areas of the city.
And we sat around the city hall and I said, you know, we need to put in office some people who y'all think would serve and would do a good job for the city.
And I said, I don't know who they are, you know what I mean, but I would prefer that we discuss it and come to some agreement as to who would best serve our community.
And if we are so inclined, why, maybe all of us can agree to support them.
I said, I don't know who they may be, but, you know, whoever, we all might pick one name.
So we did.
We didn't have any pressure on us, for sure.
So, names like Dan Davis came.
He went over and that's all right.
He represented people, represented very well the people over there.
And, you know, they were still working with the other person.
Representing the old recycling of the city.
Well, that was good, you know.
They had a picture of, you know, that would be good.
So I said, well, I want you all to support him.
And everybody in the department said, yeah, but you think Dan would make a good company.
So I went to see Dan, see if he'd serve, and he went and prod him a little bit, and his wife.
I finally got him to serve.
And the same thing came up about Lindsey.
Lindsey's up here, he's a college hero.
He's well known in the university.
You know him.
They go through all the rigmarole and run off to just pray.
Yeah, you got Lindsey to run and do what's up.
I'd go and see Lindsey at the end of the month.
He agreed to serve.
And we did that to get things started.
And it worked out very well.
I didn't mean that they wouldn't agree or disagree with me at the table, because we've had some strong disagreements.
But at any rate, they were honest disagreements.
So we did this for a while, and I thought it was very successful.
Because we could get people, otherwise we wouldn't, you know, we couldn't get people.
Because if I came to you and asked you to run, you'd say, well, I don't know anybody, I don't have any support, but if I told you, well...
There's 12 people, you know, from all areas of the city.

You know, they vote for you and possibly, you know, give $5 or $10, which, you know, any campaign expenses you can add, you'd be more inclined to, you know, accept it or at least think about it seriously.
And in this way, we've got a pretty big cross section.
We've got an engineer, we have a sociologist, Cliff Lansdell was an engineer, Joe McGrath worked with a planter, but he was back in something.
But I mean, we had a good mix across the country.
And we got along good together.
Oh, we had some, you know, some words between us once in a while, and that was to be expected.
So, this served for a while, and then that idea was dropped in favor of others who wanted to run and enter the game together.
Well, are you saying that this committee used law very newly?
Oh, no, no, no.
No, just after the... Just after the thing to get, you know... To get people on the council.
Right.
Right.
Right, okay.
This is after you were mayor, but the city went back to the ward system, and it was kind of a court-ish type of a matter.
And do you remember getting under the condition to either recount the vote, or just...
called him into the ballot, because apparently he read very badly in the ballot.
And so it was about 1976, and he was sitting, put on the ballot, picked a boy, and went back to the vote system.
And... Oh, well, you know, that was just... That was just a hazy recollection.
You remember that?
But I don't think I'll ever do that again.
Oh, well, anyway, basically, the city went back to the ward system for just two years, and then as soon as the waiting period was up, they pushed back.
Yeah.
I forget.
I remember it, but I don't recall.
I wish I'd gotten over what I had on the study out here in the back.
Yeah.
It would refresh me.
I looked at some of that material for about three weeks.
It was interesting to run across things that I had almost forgotten about.
Well, one thing that you have referred to is the historic rivalry between .
This is, it has been going on for such a long time.
Right.
Are you going to make it before?
Yeah, they, I think it started a long time ago.
You know, the student body, they had a problem with the student body in crime.
Then we incorporated in 38, anything like that.
And then they came out and stole part of our schooling.
For example, Roseberry was part of college study.
A lot of people, we thought it was in our area.
And they came out one night and took that.
They used to be six miles before we took in crime.
And they came down and expanded their boundary one night through to Rosemarie and all that area right up to our tunnel.
Was this at the time of incorporation?
No, no.
This was the second time.
Yeah, right after.
Yeah, they...
They came up and took in Rosemary.
Well, the people that lived there were university people.
That moved out on that particular area.
It wasn't in Brine at the time.
And it was in our little consolidated school district.
And when Brine took it in, when I went to Brine, we went to the Brine Independent School District.
And it hurt our little school down here.
So that created it.
You know, it was following that, that day we heard they were going to take me into an airport.
And you know, just when they were going all the way around us.
So we got together, and that particular night, we passed on first reading that all the university land is considered part of City College Station.
And that's why, you know, when you look at the map, it's so expensive.
Be that as it may, that was part of this early, you know, misunderstanding between us.
Now I did, I did institute, went there, now again, papers, newspapers weren't at the meeting.
The system whereby, well now this was in the era of Jack Zuby, and what's her name?
What was her name?
I went through several layers of crime.
No, no, she wasn't a mayor, but she was a very dominant figure in the crime commission.
And I instituted meetings with the crime commission at the Monaghan, whereby we need to be honest with each other and not
pull these tricks.
The first meeting, when I spoke to Michael, I didn't come out and it was very plain as to the purpose of the meeting.
As far as I was concerned, I enjoyed the fellowship.
We could sit down and have a drink together.
We could have a good meal.
You know, we separated ourselves so we could make it again.
But I wanted us to, if we're going to fight each other, let's do it in a dynamic way or in a sense that
We're not all caught short all the time on short ends of the stick.
Otherwise, we're just going to fight with each other.
So I wanted us to let our hair down and let each other know what we were planning to do, what we intended to do in our respective city.
And this way, maybe we could coordinate or cooperate with many projects.
At that time, we were getting quite a bit of water coming.
a grind and we still get some but they they had us over the night and we resolved them to our satisfaction so we didn't have too much of a problem but we we had problems and uh
So we would meet every two months while I was there.
The whole term?
Yeah.
Five years?
Yeah.
And then, you know, I'd bring a board and show them the related things that we were doing.
Or had planned it for what we had done since the last round.
Just to enlighten them.
And they, in turn, jacked Zuby.
And a couple others on the front.
And they did the same thing.
And for a while there, we had excellent rapport.
I mean, you know, they could start something, but, you know, and so that we wouldn't, you know, you don't want to be cut.
Yeah, right.
So, but then along came the open meeting law, and that ended up affecting everything, and we couldn't do that.

because he couldn't say things something without you don't mean maybe something you didn't want to pay for a while yet you wanted to work up the data presented to the people come out with a half-cocked idea and that's just like this way for the council that's an exception one person was
before the last vote.
And when they had the last vote on the path, the mayor voted for it away from them.
I mean, they were influenced by the Republicans.
And they were made by them.
And they shouldn't do that.
You know, you have a tendency to be influenced by people, but sometimes you have to
go against the tide for the betterment of more people.
And some people are reluctant to do it.
That's something that I don't know whether they did right or wrong in this matter before, because I didn't know both sides myself sufficiently.
Was it still a possibility that you didn't do it then?
Oh, well, I'm doing this on my own.
Well, a lot of them are interested in what I find out about the city, but I'm doing this on my own.
Oh, but the plans are for sure?
Well, they are for now.
Oh, for now.
I'm sure it's fine.
Excuse me, I have an allergy.
My nostrils are clogged up.
Well, for the most part, yeah.
I tried to get over.
Now, we have this problem, as I explained to you about the taxing and these things.
And it took a while to get all these going.
You can't do everything, you know, overnight.
It took me a long time to write up that plan.
And then I worked up the scheme for the library and all of that kind of stuff.
I believe that's all that I have.
If there's anything that you might want to add, but this has been most helpful as far as just locating different aspects.
Well, if there's anything, you know, when you're writing, if there's anything that you come across that you think that might help, let me know.
You know, I may be able to think, or I might be able to check on some of the stuff that I have.
Oh, I really appreciate that.
Because I've noticed, you know, just a little writing that I've done, I have questions, I have a lot of material, but then there's something that I'm used to.
Well, you know, with all the letters that you read in the file, the whole story's going to change.
That's right, I know.
I know it is.
It's like, what's his name over at the library?
You know, he's working on a document.
He wrote it.
He's writing a history of Texas sports.
Oh, with David Chapman.
Yeah.
Yeah, yeah.
I worked under him.
Oh, you did?
Uh-huh.
Oh, okay.
Well, I provided him with a lot of stuff.
And I still haven't read what he worked up.
Apparently he did a good job, and he checked a lot of, well, I don't know, laboratory, Washington Museum, any other places.
I have some material here that goes back to the early days.
Some other stuff.
But I still haven't read that.
I want to get a copy of it.
I'd like to see what it says on it.
and a little bit of a period of time.
I want to see how it fits.
I mean, with the university.
Oh, with the university.
Oh.
Yeah.
Yeah, but yeah.
Oh, just one of these period of time.
I was acting director after five.
We had a very severe fire situation going on in the condo.
We had all foods out next door.
Bones were burning.
The foundation came out and set up the canteen, and the Red Cross was out there.
The Rocky Mountains came down and left a spectacular splash.
the law and they were broadcasting all of the information.
All of the foreign stories, you know.
I was under the gun from the university and then the industry, the forest industry, crying out to do something.
All this was going on.
We were losing personnel that were going to other agencies and so on.
I was just
I had a hard time.
What year?
Was it at the same time you did it?
No, I think it was before.
I was going to say, I hope you wouldn't have all those troubles all there at one time.
Well, I did work up, well, I don't want to give a big difference, but it seems like I've been bragging a lot about it.
I had a few brownie points with him, but he went off while he took a brownie point.
But he and his office call one day, they wanted to send them quick and line up on some of the things I'd been engaged with.
I'm not going to
